definition.value: A sulfonamide consisting of pyrimidine having methyl substituents at the 2- and 6-positions and a 4-aminobenzenesulfonamido group at the 4-position.
A class of cyclodepsipeptides which are secreted by the plant pathogen Pseudomonas syringae. Composed from nine nonribosomally synthesised amino acids bonded to a fatty acid hydrocarbon tail.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of tiotropium bromide. Used for maintenance treatment of airflow obstruction in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.

An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a 3-chloro-2-methylphenyl group. Tolfenamic acid is used specifically for relieving the pain of migraine. It also shows anticancer activity.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of triprolidine hydrochloride. A sedating antihistamine, it is used for the symptomatic relief of uticaria, rhinitis, and various pruritic skin disorders.
A hydrate that is the heptahydrate form of zinc sulfate.
The hydrochloride hydrate salt of ziprasidone.
A monosaccharide derivative that is the carboxamide of beta-D-glucuronic acid
A 3-coumaric acid that is phenol substituted with trans-2-propenoic acid at position C-3.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of nonanoic acid that in methyl ester form has significant nematicidal activity.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of heptanoic acid; shown in myocardial ischaemia/reperfusion studies to increase levels of C4 Kreb's cycle intermediates.
A C17 saturated fatty acid and trace component of fats in ruminants.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of margaric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A straight-chain, eleven-carbon saturated medium-chain fatty acid found in body fluids; the most fungitoxic of the C7:0 - C18:0 fatty acid series.
A medium-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of undecanoic acid; used in tandem with testosterone cation in the treatment of male hypogonadism. Major species at pH 7.3.
A coumarate that is the conjugate base of 4-coumaric acid.
The trans-isomer of 4-coumaric acid.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion and the conjugate base of 6-hydroxyhexanoic acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group.
The L-enantiomer of cysteinium.
A neoxanthin in which all of the double bonds have trans geometry.
The D-enantiomer of cysteinium.
An aldehydo-paratose that has D-configuration.
A thiocarboxamide consiting of acetamide having the oxygen replaced by sulfur.
A glycosylfructose isolated from Daphnia magna.
A pyridinemonocarboxylate that is the conjugate base of nicotinic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A metal chloride salt with a K(+) counterion.
A magnesium salt having sulfate as the counterion.
The cis-isomer of aconitic acid.
The trans-isomer of aconitic acid.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is 2,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a methyl group.
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is the enol-form of phenylpyruvic acid, consisting of acrylic acid having a hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and a phenyl group at the 3-position.
